cuisine: Asian
servings: 2
---

Pour the @water{300%ml} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling,
add the @star anise{1} and @salt{0.25%tsp}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g},
lower the heat to medium and pop a lid on the pan. Leave to cook for
~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to
the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will
continue to cook in its own steam).

Whilst the rice cooks, halve the @bell peppers{2} and discard the core and
seeds. Chop into 2cm sized chunks. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into
1cm chunks. Trim the @spring onion{1} then thinly slice. Peel and grate the
@garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}
and set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on a medium high heat. Once
hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{150%g} and fry until golden stirring frequently,
~{3-4%minutes}. Remove to a #bowl{}. Meanwhile, put the chopped peppers and
brown onion in a large bowl and mix with the @cornflour{10%g}. In a small bowl
mix together the @ketjap manis{50%ml}, @rice vinegar{30%ml}, garlic,
@ginger puree{1}, and @water{75%ml}.

Pop your empty frying pan back on medium high heat with a drizzle of oil.
Add the floured peppers and onion to the pan. Fry until slightly charred and
softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once softened add the mushrooms and pour in the
sauce mixture. Stir together well. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the sauce is nice and sticky, add the @Chinese leaf{120%g}(chopped), stir
fry until it wilted and piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste and add @salt{} and
@pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Remove the star anise from your rice and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Divide
the rice between your plates, top with the sweet and sour veg. Sprinkle on
the spring onion and chopped peanuts. Enjoy!